03711nam a22005535i 9780300156492DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20092009ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001564927 a10.12987/97803001564922doi  a(DE-B1597)485888  a(OCoLC)640419313  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aBR128.R7 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a270.11 aJohnson, Luke Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmong the Gentiles :bGreco-Roman Religion and Christianity /cLuke Timothy Johnson. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Anchor Yale Bible Reference Library0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe question of Christianity’s relation to the other religions of the world is more pertinent and difficult today than ever before. While Christianity’s historical failure to appreciate or actively engage Judaism is notorious, Christianity’s even more shoddy record with respect to “pagan” religions is less understood. Christians have inherited a virtually unanimous theological tradition that thinks of paganism in terms of demonic possession, and of Christian missions as a rescue operation that saves pagans from inherently evil practices. In undertaking this fresh inquiry into early Christianity and Greco-Roman paganism, Luke Timothy Johnson begins with a broad definition of religion as a way of life organized around convictions and experiences concerning ultimate power. In the tradition of William James’s Variety of Religious Experience, he identifies four distinct ways of being religious: religion as participation in benefits, as moral transformation, as transcending the world, and as stabilizing the world. Using these criteria as the basis for his exploration of Christianity and paganism, Johnson finds multiple points of similarity in religious sensibility.Christianity’s failure to adequately come to grips with its first pagan neighbors, Johnson asserts, inhibits any effort to engage positively with adherents of various world religions. This thoughtful and passionate study should help break down the walls between Christianity and other religious traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChristianity and other religionsxGreek. 0aChristianity and other religionsxRoman. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aPaganismxHistory. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015649240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300156492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300156492/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles